# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hiroaki-nakanishi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A major worldwide financial crisis centered in the United States took place in 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The causes included excessive speculation on property values by both homeowners and financial institutions, leading to the 2000s United States housing bubble.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was exacerbated by predatory lending for subprime mortgages and by deficiencies in regulation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Cash out refinancings had fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The first phase of the crisis was the subprime mortgage crisis, which began in early 2007, as mortgage-backed securities (MBS) tied to U.S. real estate, and a vast web of derivatives linked to those MBS collapsed in value.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A liquidity crisis spread to global institutions by mid-2007 and climaxed with the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers in September 2008, which triggered a stock market crash and bank runs in several countries.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in late-2007, as well as the United States bear market of 2007–2009.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was also a contributor to the 2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis and the euro area crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As the Federal Reserve ("Fed") lowered the federal funds rate from 2000 to 2003, institutions increasingly targeted low-income homebuyers, largely belonging to racial minorities, with high-risk loans; this development went unattended by regulators.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As interest rates rose from 2004 to 2006, the cost of mortgages rose and the demand for housing fell; in early 2007, as more U.S. subprime mortgage holders began defaulting on their repayments, lenders went bankrupt, culminating in the bankruptcy of New Century Financial in April.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As demand and prices continued to fall, the financial contagion spread to global credit markets by August 2007, and central banks began injecting liquidity.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In March 2008, Bear Stearns, the fifth-largest U.S. investment bank, was sold to JPMorgan Chase in a "fire sale" backed by Fed financing.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In response to the growing crisis, governments around the world deployed massive bailouts of financial institutions and used monetary policy and fiscal policies to prevent an economic collapse of the global financial system.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] By July 2008, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, companies which together owned or guaranteed half of the U.S. housing market, verged on collapse; the Housing and Economic Recovery Act of 2008 enabled the federal government to seize them on September 7.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] On October 3, Congress passed the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, authorizing the Treasury Department to purchase toxic assets and bank stocks through the $700 billion Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Fed began a program of quantitative easing by buying treasury bonds and other assets, such as MBS, and the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act, signed in February 2009 by newly elected president Barack Obama, included a range of measures intended to preserve existing jobs and create new ones.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] These initiatives combined, coupled with actions taken in other countries, ended the worst of the Great Recession by mid-2009.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Assessments of the crisis's impact in the U.S. vary, but suggest that some 8.7 million jobs were lost, causing unemployment to rise from 5% in 2007 to a high of 10% in October 2009.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The percentage of citizens living in poverty rose from 12.5% in 2007 to 15.1% in 2010.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by 53% between October 2007 and March 2009, and some estimates suggest that one in four households lost 75% or more of their net worth.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was passed, overhauling financial regulations.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was opposed by many Republicans, and it was weakened by the Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act in 2018.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were also adopted by countries around the world.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in mid-2007.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was among the five worst financial crises the world had experienced and led to a loss of more than $2 trillion from the global economy.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 (~$15 trillion in 2024) trillion.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The increase in cash out refinancings, as home values rose, fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many financial institutions owned investments whose value was based on home mortgages such as mortgage-backed securities, or credit derivatives used to insure them against failure, which declined in value significantly.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The International Monetary Fund estimated that large U.S. and European banks lost more than $1 trillion on toxic assets and from bad loans from January 2007 to September 2009.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Lack of investor confidence in bank solvency and declines in credit availability led to plummeting stock and commodity prices in late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis rapidly spread into a global economic shock, resulting in several bank failures.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Economies worldwide slowed during this period since credit tightened and international trade declined.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Housing markets suffered and unemployment soared, resulting in evictions and foreclosures.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] From its peak in the second quarter of 2007 at $61.4 trillion, household wealth in the United States fell $11 trillion, to $50.4 trillion by the end of the first quarter of 2009, resulting in a decline in consumption, then a decline in business investment.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the fourth quarter of 2008, the quarter-over-quarter decline in real GDP in the U.S. was 8.4%.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The U.S. unemployment rate peaked at 11.0% in October 2009, the highest rate since 1983 and roughly twice the pre-crisis rate.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The average hours per work week declined to 33, the lowest level since the government began collecting the data in 1964.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The economic crisis started in the U.S. but spread to the rest of the world.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. consumption accounted for more than a third of the growth in global consumption between 2000 and 2007 and the rest of the world depended on the U.S. consumer as a source of demand.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Toxic securities were owned by corporate and institutional investors globally.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Derivatives such as credit default swaps also increased the linkage between large financial institutions.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The de-leveraging of financial institutions, as assets were sold to pay back obligations that could not be refinanced in frozen credit markets, further accelerated the solvency crisis and caused a decrease in international trade.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Reductions in the growth rates of developing countries were due to falls in trade, commodity prices, investment and remittances sent from migrant workers (example: Armenia).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] States with fragile political systems feared that investors from Western states would withdraw their money because of the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In effect, the central banks went from being the "lender of last resort" to the "lender of only resort" for a significant portion of the economy.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In some cases the Fed was considered the "buyer of last resort".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] During the fourth quarter of 2008, these central banks purchased US$2.5 trillion (~$3.57 trillion in 2024) of government debt and troubled private assets from banks.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was the largest liquidity injection into the credit market, and the largest monetary policy action in world history.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve created then-significant amounts of new currency as a method to combat the liquidity trap.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Bailouts came in the form of trillions of dollars of loans, asset purchases, guarantees, and direct spending.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Significant controversy accompanied the bailouts, such as in the case of the AIG bonus payments controversy, leading to the development of a variety of "decision making frameworks", to help balance competing policy interests during times of financial crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Alistair Darling, the U.K.'s Chancellor of the Exchequer at the time of the crisis, stated in 2018 that Britain came within hours of "a breakdown of law and order" the day that Royal Bank of Scotland was bailed-out.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Instead of financing more domestic loans, some banks instead spent some of the stimulus money in more profitable areas such as investing in emerging markets and foreign currencies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In July 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was enacted in the United States to "promote the financial stability of the United States".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were adopted worldwide.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Since the 2008 financial crisis, consumer regulators in America have more closely supervised sellers of credit cards and home mortgages in order to deter anticompetitive practices that led to the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] At least two major reports on the causes of the crisis were produced by the U.S.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Congress: the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission report, released January 2011, and a report by the United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations entitled Wall Street and the Financial Crisis: Anatomy of a Financial Collapse, released April 2011.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In total, 47 bankers served jail time as a result of the crisis, over half of whom were from Iceland, where the crisis was the most severe and led to the collapse of all three major Icelandic banks.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In April 2012, Geir Haarde of Iceland became the only politician to be convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the aftermath of the crisis, U.S. authorities intensified enforcement actions against financial misconduct, including high-profile insider trading prosecutions such as that of Raj Rajaratnam, who was convicted in 2011.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Only one banker in the United States served jail time as a result of the crisis, Kareem Serageldin, a banker at Credit Suisse who was sentenced to 30 months in jail and returned $24.6 million in compensation for manipulating bond prices to hide $1 billion of losses.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] No individuals in the United Kingdom were convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Goldman Sachs*, Goldman Sachs paid a $550 million civil penalty and acknowledged that its marketing materials for CDO contained incomplete information, settling securities fraud charges after allegedly anticipating the financial crisis and selling toxic investments to its clients.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] With fewer resources to risk in creative destruction, the number of patent applications was flat, compared to exponential increases in patent application in prior years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Typical American families did not fare well, nor did the "wealthy-but-not-wealthiest" families just beneath the pyramid's top.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, half of the poorest families in the United States did not have wealth declines at all during the crisis because they generally did not own financial investments whose value could fluctuate.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve surveyed 4,000 households from 2007 to 2009, and found that the total wealth of 63% of all Americans declined in that period and 77% of the richest families had a decrease in total wealth, while only 50% of those on the bottom of the pyramid suffered a decrease.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The following is a timeline of the major events of the financial crisis, including government responses, and the subsequent economic recovery.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the table, the names of emerging and developing economies are shown in boldface type, while the names of developed economies are in Roman (regular) type.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The expansion of central bank lending in response to the crisis was not confined to the Federal Reserve's provision of aid to individual financial institutions.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve has also conducted several innovative lending programs to improve liquidity and strengthen different financial institutions and markets, such as Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In this case, the major problem in the market is the lack of free cash reserves and flows to secure the loans.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve took many steps to deal with financial market liquidity worries.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] One of these steps was a credit line for major traders, who act as the Fed's partners in open market activities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, loan programs were set up to make the money market mutual funds and commercial paper market more flexible.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility (TALF) was put in place thanks to a joint effort with the US Department of the Treasury.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This plan made it easier for consumers and businesses to get credit by giving Americans who owned high-quality asset-backed securities more credit.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Before the crisis, the Federal Reserve's stocks of Treasury securities were sold to pay for the increase in credit.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This method was meant to keep banks from trying to give out their extra savings, which could cause the federal funds rate to drop below where it was supposed to be.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, in October 2008, the Federal Reserve was granted the power to provide banks with interest payments on their surplus reserves.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This created a motivation for banks to retain their reserves instead of disbursing them, thus reducing the need for the Federal Reserve to hedge its increased lending by decreases in alternative assets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Money market funds also went through runs when people lost faith in the market.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] To keep it from getting worse, the Fed said it would give money to mutual fund companies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Department of Treasury said that it would briefly cover the assets of the fund.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Both of these things helped get the fund market back to normal, which helped the commercial paper market, which most businesses use to run.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The FDIC also did several things, such as raising the insurance cap from $100,000 to $250,000, to boost customer trust.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] They engaged in quantitative easing, which added more than $4 trillion to the financial system and got banks to start lending again, both to each other and to people.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many homeowners who were trying to keep their homes from going into default got housing credits.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A package of policies was passed that let borrowers refinance their loans even though the value of their homes was less than what they still owed on their mortgages.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The relaxing of credit lending standards by investment banks and commercial banks allowed for a significant increase in subprime lending.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime had not become less risky; Wall Street just accepted this higher risk.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Due to competition between mortgage lenders for revenue and market share, and when the supply of creditworthy borrowers was limited, mortgage lenders relaxed underwriting standards and originated riskier mortgages to less creditworthy borrowers.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the view of some analysts, the relatively conservative government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) policed mortgage originators and maintained relatively high underwriting standards prior to 2003.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] However, as market power shifted from securitizers to originators, and as intense competition from private securitizers undermined GSE power, mortgage standards declined and risky loans proliferated.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The riskiest loans were originated in 2004–2007, the years of the most intense competition between securitizers and the lowest market share for the GSEs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The GSEs eventually relaxed their standards to try to catch up with the private banks.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Depending on how "subprime" mortgages are defined, they remained below 10% of all mortgage originations until 2004, when they rose to nearly 20% and remained there through the 2005–2006 peak of the United States housing bubble.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Although they concede that governmental policies had some role in causing the crisis, they contend that GSE loans performed better than loans securitized by private investment banks, and performed better than some loans originated by institutions that held loans in their own portfolios.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In his dissent to the majority report of the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, conservative American Enterprise Institute fellow Peter J.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Based upon information in the SEC's December 2011 securities fraud case against six former executives of Fannie and Freddie, Peter Wallison and Edward Pinto estimated that, in 2008, Fannie and Freddie held 13 million substandard loans totaling over $2 trillion.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the early and mid-2000s, the Bush administration called numerous times for investigations into the safety and soundness of the GSEs and their swelling portfolio of subprime mortgages.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The hearings never resulted in new legislation or formal investigation of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, as many of the committee members refused to accept the report and instead rebuked OFHEO for their attempt at regulation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Some, such as Wallison, believe this was an early warning to the systemic risk that the growing market in subprime mortgages posed to the U.S. financial system that went unheeded.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Sub-prime loans made by CRA-covered institutions constituted a 3% market share of LMI loans in 1998, but in the run-up to the crisis, fully 25% of all subprime lending occurred at CRA-covered institutions and another 25% of subprime loans had some connection with CRA.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] To other analysts the delay between CRA rule changes in 1995 and the explosion of subprime lending is not surprising, and does not exonerate the CRA.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They contend that there were two, connected causes to the crisis: the relaxation of underwriting standards in 1995 and the ultra-low interest rates initiated by the Federal Reserve after the terrorist attack on September 11, 2001.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Both causes had to be in place before the crisis could take place.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Critics also point out that publicly announced CRA loan commitments were massive, totaling $4.5 trillion in the years between 1994 and 2007.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They also argue that the Federal Reserve's classification of CRA loans as "prime" is based on the faulty and self-serving assumption that high-interest-rate loans (3 percentage points over average) equal "subprime" loans.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Others have pointed out that there were not enough of these loans made to cause a crisis of this magnitude.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By March 2011, the FDIC had paid out $9 billion (c. $12.3 billion in 2024) to cover losses on bad loans at 165 failed financial institutions.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Congressional Budget Office estimated, in June 2011, that the bailout to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac exceeds $300 billion (c. $411 billion in 2024) (calculated by adding the fair value deficits of the entities to the direct bailout funds at the time).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other words, bubbles in both markets developed even though only the residential market was affected by these potential causes.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] *residential housing* bubble (as opposed to other types of bubbles) led to financial crisis was that it was supported by a huge number of substandard loans—generally with low or no downpayments.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Krugman's contention (that the growth of a commercial real estate bubble indicates that U.S. housing policy was not the cause of the crisis) is challenged by additional analysis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After researching the default of commercial loans during the financial crisis, Xudong An and Anthony B.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Business journalist Kimberly Amadeo reported: "The first signs of decline in residential real estate occurred in 2006.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Three years later, commercial real estate started feeling the effects." Denice A.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Between 1998 and 2006, the price of the typical American house increased by 124%.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During the 1980s and 1990s, the national median home price ranged from 2.9 to 3.1 times median household income.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By contrast, this ratio increased to 4.0 in 2004, and 4.6 in 2006.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This housing bubble resulted in many homeowners refinancing their homes at lower interest rates, or financing consumer spending by taking out second mortgages secured by the price appreciation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In a Peabody Award-winning program, NPR correspondents argued that a "Giant Pool of Money" (represented by $70 trillion in worldwide fixed income investments) sought higher yields than those offered by U.S.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This pool of money had roughly doubled in size from 2000 to 2007, yet the supply of relatively safe, income generating investments had not grown as fast.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Investment banks on Wall Street answered this demand with products such as the mortgage-backed security and the collateralized debt obligation that were assigned safe ratings by the credit rating agencies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In effect, Wall Street connected this pool of money to the mortgage market in the US, with enormous fees accruing to those throughout the mortgage supply chain, from the mortgage broker selling the loans to small banks that funded the brokers and the large investment banks behind them.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By approximately 2003, the supply of mortgages originated at traditional lending standards had been exhausted, and continued strong demand began to drive down lending standards.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The collateralized debt obligation in particular enabled financial institutions to obtain investor funds to finance subprime and other lending, extending or increasing the housing bubble and generating large fees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This essentially places cash payments from multiple mortgages or other debt obligations into a single pool from which specific securities draw in a specific sequence of priority.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Those securities first in line received investment-grade ratings from rating agencies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Securities with lower priority had lower credit ratings but theoretically a higher rate of return on the amount invested.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2008, average U.S. housing prices had declined by over 20% from their mid-2006 peak.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As prices declined, borrowers with adjustable-rate mortgages could not refinance to avoid the higher payments associated with rising interest rates and began to default.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During 2007, lenders began foreclosure proceedings on nearly 1.3 million properties, a 79% increase over 2006.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased to 2.3 million in 2008, an 81% increase vs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By August 2008, approximately 9% of all U.S. mortgages outstanding were either delinquent or in foreclosure.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2009, this had risen to 14.4%.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After the bubble burst, Australian economist John Quiggin wrote: "And, unlike the Great Depression, this crisis was entirely the product of financial markets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Lower interest rates encouraged borrowing.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] From 2000 to 2003, the Federal Reserve lowered the federal funds rate target from 6.5% to 1.0%.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This was done to soften the effects of the collapse of the dot-com bubble and the September 11 attacks, as well as to combat a perceived risk of deflation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As early as 2002, it was apparent that credit was fueling housing instead of business investment as some economists went so far as to advocate that the Fed "needs to create a housing bubble to replace the Nasdaq bubble".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, empirical studies using data from advanced countries show that excessive credit growth contributed greatly to the severity of the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Additional downward pressure on interest rates was created by a growing U.S. current account deficit, which peaked along with the housing bubble in 2006.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke explained how trade deficits required the U.S. to borrow money from abroad, in the process bidding up bond prices and lowering interest rates.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bernanke explained that between 1996 and 2004, the U.S. current account deficit increased by $650 billion, from 1.5% to 5.8% of GDP.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financing these deficits required the country to borrow large sums from abroad, much of it from countries running trade surpluses.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] These were mainly the emerging economies in Asia and oil-exporting nations.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The balance of payments identity requires that a country (such as the US) running a current account deficit also have a capital account (investment) surplus of the same amount.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Hence large and growing amounts of foreign funds (capital) flowed into the U.S. to finance its imports.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] All of this created demand for various types of financial assets, raising the prices of those assets while lowering interest rates.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign investors had these funds to lend either because they had very high personal savings rates (as high as 40% in China) or because of high oil prices.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Ben Bernanke referred to this as a "saving glut".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A flood of funds (capital or liquidity) reached the U.S. financial markets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign governments supplied funds by purchasing Treasury bonds and thus avoided much of the direct effect of the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households used funds borrowed from foreigners to finance consumption or to bid up the prices of housing and financial assets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financial institutions invested foreign funds in mortgage-backed securities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Fed then raised the Fed funds rate significantly between July 2004 and July 2006.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This contributed to an increase in one-year and five-year adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) rates, making ARM interest rate resets more expensive for homeowners.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This may have also contributed to the deflation of the housing bubble, as asset prices generally move inversely to interest rates.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] It became riskier to speculate in housing.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. housing and financial assets dramatically declined in value after the housing bubble burst.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime lending standards declined in the U.S.: in early 2000, a subprime borrower had a FICO score of 660 or less.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By 2005, many lenders dropped the required FICO score to 620, making it much easier to qualify for prime loans and making subprime lending a riskier business.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Proof of income and assets were de-emphasized.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Loans at first required full documentation, then low documentation, then no documentation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] One subprime mortgage product that gained wide acceptance was the no income, no job, no asset verification required (NINJA) mortgage.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Informally, these loans were aptly referred to as "liar loans" because they encouraged borrowers to be less than honest in the loan application process.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Testimony given to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission by whistleblower Richard M.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bowen III on events during his tenure as the Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup, where he was responsible for over 220 professional underwriters, suggests that by 2006 and 2007, the collapse of mortgage underwriting standards was endemic.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] His testimony stated that by 2006, 60% of mortgages purchased by Citigroup from some 1,600 mortgage companies were "defective" (were not underwritten to policy, or did not contain all policy-required documents).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This, despite the fact that each of these 1,600 originators was contractually responsible (certified via representations and warrantees) that its mortgage originations met Citigroup standards.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, during 2007, "defective mortgages (from mortgage originators contractually bound to perform underwriting to Citi's standards) increased to over 80% of production".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The analysis, conducted on behalf of 23 investment and commercial banks, including 7 "too big to fail" banks, additionally showed that 28% of the sampled loans did not meet the minimal standards of any issuer.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Clayton's analysis further showed that 39% of these loans (i.e. those not meeting *any* issuer's minimal underwriting standards) were subsequently securitized and sold to investors.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Predatory lending refers to the practice of unscrupulous lenders enticing borrowers to enter into unfair or abusive secured loans for inappropriate purposes.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In May 2009, Bank of America modified 64,000 Countrywide loans as a result.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] When housing prices decreased, homeowners in ARMs then had little incentive to pay their monthly payments, since their home equity had disappeared.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This caused Countrywide's financial condition to deteriorate, ultimately resulting in a decision by the Office of Thrift Supervision to seize the lender.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Former employees from Ameriquest, which was the United States' leading wholesale lender, described a system in which they were pushed to falsify mortgage documents and then sell the mortgages to Wall Street banks eager to make fast profits.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] There is growing evidence that such mortgage frauds may be a cause of the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] According to Barry Eichengreen, the roots of the financial crisis lay in the deregulation of financial markets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A 2012 OECD study suggested that bank regulation based on the Basel accords encouraged unconventional business practices and contributed to or reinforced the financial crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other cases, laws were changed or enforcement weakened in parts of the financial system.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Prior to the crisis, financial institutions became highly leveraged, increasing their appetite for risky investments and reducing their resilience in case of losses.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Much of this leverage was achieved using complex financial instruments such as off-balance sheet securitization and derivatives, which made it difficult for creditors and regulators to monitor and try to reduce financial institution risk levels.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households and financial institutions became increasingly indebted or overleveraged during the years preceding the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased their vulnerability to the collapse of the housing bubble and worsened the ensuing economic downturn.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Free cash used by consumers from home equity extraction doubled from $627 billion in 2001 to $1,428 billion in 2005 as the housing bubble built, a total of nearly $5 trillion over the period, contributing to economic growth worldwide.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 trillion (c. $15 trillion in 2024).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. household debt as a percentage of annual disposable personal income was 127% at the end of 2007, versus 77% in 1990.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1981, U.S. private debt was 123% of GDP; by the third quarter of 2008, it was 290%.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From 2004 to 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks each significantly increased their financial leverage, which increased their vulnerability to a financial shock.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Changes in capital requirements, intended to keep U.S. banks competitive with their European counterparts, allowed lower *risk weightings* for AAA-rated securities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The shift from first-loss tranches to AAA-rated tranches was seen by regulators as a risk reduction that compensated the higher leverage.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These five institutions reported over $4.1 trillion in debt for fiscal year 2007, about 30% of U.S. nominal GDP for 2007.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Lehman Brothers went bankrupt and was liquidated, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became commercial banks, subjecting themselves to more stringent regulation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With the exception of Lehman, these companies required or received government support.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, two U.S. government-sponsored enterprises, owned or guaranteed nearly $5 trillion (c. $7.13 trillion in 2024) trillion in mortgage obligations at the time they were placed into conservatorship by the U.S. government in September 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These seven entities were highly leveraged and had $9 trillion in debt or guarantee obligations; yet they were not subject to the same regulation as depository banks.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Behavior that may be optimal for an individual, such as saving more during adverse economic conditions, can be detrimental if too many individuals pursue the same behavior, as ultimately one person's consumption is another person's income.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Too many consumers attempting to save or pay down debt simultaneously is called the paradox of thrift and can cause or deepen a recession.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Hyman Minsky also described a "paradox of deleveraging" as financial institutions that have too much leverage (debt relative to equity) cannot all de-leverage simultaneously without significant declines in the value of their assets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The term financial innovation refers to the ongoing development of financial products designed to achieve particular client objectives, such as offsetting a particular risk exposure (such as the default of a borrower) or to assist with obtaining financing.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The usage of these products expanded dramatically in the years leading up to the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These products vary in complexity and the ease with which they can be valued on the books of financial institutions.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] CDO issuance grew from an estimated $20 billion in Q1 2004 to its peak of over $180 billion by Q1 2007, then declined back under $20 billion by Q1 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, the credit quality of CDO's declined from 2000 to 2007, as the level of subprime and other non-prime mortgage debt increased from 5% to 36% of CDO assets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As described in the section on subprime lending, the CDS and portfolio of CDS called synthetic CDO enabled a theoretically infinite amount to be wagered on the finite value of housing loans outstanding, provided that buyers and sellers of the derivatives could be found.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, buying a CDS to insure a CDO ended up giving the seller the same risk as if they owned the CDO, when those CDO's became worthless.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This boom in innovative financial products went hand in hand with more complexity.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] It multiplied the number of actors connected to a single mortgage (including mortgage brokers, specialized originators, the securitizers and their due diligence firms, managing agents and trading desks, and finally investors, insurances and providers of repo funding).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Instead of spreading risk this provided the ground for fraudulent acts, misjudgments and finally market collapse.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists have studied the crisis as an instance of cascades in financial networks, where institutions' instability destabilized other institutions and led to knock-on effects.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Mortgage risks were underestimated by almost all institutions in the chain from originator to investor by underweighting the possibility of falling housing prices based on historical trends of the past 50 years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While financial derivatives and structured products helped partition and shift risk between financial participants, it was the underestimation of falling housing prices and the resultant losses that led to aggregate risk.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For a variety of reasons, market participants did not accurately measure the risk inherent with financial innovation such as MBS and CDOs or understand its effect on the overall stability of the financial system.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The pricing model for CDOs clearly did not reflect the level of risk they introduced into the system.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] AIG insured obligations of various financial institutions through the usage of credit default swaps.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The basic CDS transaction involved AIG receiving a premium in exchange for a promise to pay money to party A in the event party B defaulted.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] However, AIG did not have the financial strength to support its many CDS commitments as the crisis progressed and was taken over by the government in September 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. taxpayers provided over $180 billion in government loans and investments in AIG during 2008 and early 2009, through which the money flowed to various counterparties to CDS transactions, including many large global financial institutions.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission (FCIC) made the major government study of the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The limitations of a widely used financial model also were not properly understood.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This formula assumed that the price of CDS was correlated with and could predict the correct price of mortgage-backed securities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Because it was highly tractable, it rapidly came to be used by a huge percentage of CDO and CDS investors, issuers, and rating agencies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As financial assets became more complex and harder to value, investors were reassured by the fact that the international bond rating agencies and bank regulators accepted as valid some complex mathematical models that showed the risks were much smaller than they actually were.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] George Soros commented that "The super-boom got out of hand when the new products became so complicated that the authorities could no longer calculate the risks and started relying on the risk management methods of the banks themselves.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Similarly, the rating agencies relied on the information provided by the originators of synthetic products.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A conflict of interest between investment management professional and institutional investors, combined with a global glut in investment capital, led to bad investments by asset managers in over-priced credit assets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Professional investment managers generally are compensated based on the volume of client assets under management.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is, therefore, an incentive for asset managers to expand their assets under management in order to maximize their compensation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As the glut in global investment capital caused the yields on credit assets to decline, asset managers were faced with the choice of either investing in assets where returns did not reflect true credit risk or returning funds to clients.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Many asset managers continued to invest client funds in over-priced (under-yielding) investments, to the detriment of their clients, so they could maintain their assets under management.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] They supported this choice with a "plausible deniability" of the risks associated with subprime-based credit assets because the loss experience with early "vintages" of subprime loans was so low.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the dominance of the above formula, there are documented attempts of the financial industry, occurring before the crisis, to address the formula limitations, specifically the lack of dependence dynamics and the poor representation of extreme events.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The volume *Credit Correlation: Life After Copulas*, published in 2007 by World Scientific, summarizes a 2006 conference held by Merrill Lynch in London where several practitioners attempted to propose models rectifying some of the copula limitations.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] See also the article by Donnelly and Embrechts and the book by Brigo, Pallavicini and Torresetti, that reports relevant warnings and research on CDOs appeared in 2006.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is strong evidence that the riskiest, worst performing mortgages were funded through the "shadow banking system" and that competition from the shadow banking system may have pressured more traditional institutions to lower their underwriting standards and originate riskier loans.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These entities became critical to the credit markets underpinning the financial system, but were not subject to the same regulatory controls.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, these entities were vulnerable because of asset–liability mismatch, meaning that they borrowed short-term in liquid markets to purchase long-term, illiquid and risky assets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that disruptions in credit markets would force them to engage in rapid deleveraging, selling their long-term assets at depressed prices.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Paul Krugman, laureate of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences, described the run on the shadow banking system as the "core of what happened" to cause the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He referred to this lack of controls as "malign neglect" and argued that regulation should have been imposed on all banking-like activity.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Without the ability to obtain investor funds in exchange for most types of mortgage-backed securities or asset-backed commercial paper, investment banks and other entities in the shadow banking system could not provide funds to mortgage firms and other corporations.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that nearly one-third of the U.S. lending mechanism was frozen and continued to be frozen into June 2009.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While traditional banks raised their lending standards, it was the collapse of the shadow banking system that was the primary cause of the reduction in funds available for borrowing.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Caballero, Emmanuel Farhi, and Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas argued that the financial crisis was attributable to "global asset scarcity, which led to large capital flows toward the United States and to the creation of asset bubbles that eventually burst".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Long-only commodity index funds became popular – by one estimate investment increased from $90 billion in 2006 to $200 billion at the end of 2007, while commodity prices increased 71% – which raised concern as to whether these index funds caused the commodity bubble.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cause of the global asset bubble can be partially attributable to the global savings glut.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As theorized by Andrew Metrick, the demand for safe assets following the Asian Financial Crisis coupled with the lack of circulating treasuries created an unmet demand for "risk free" assets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Thus, institutional investors like sovereign wealth funds and pension funds began purchasing synthetic safe assets like Triple-A Mortgage Backed Securities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As a consequence, the demand for so-called safe assets fueled the free flow of capital into housing in the United States.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This greatly worsened the crisis as banks and other financial institutions were incentivized to issue more mortgages than before.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Some commentators and economists associated with the Austrian School of economics, including former U.S.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Congressman Ron Paul and historian Tom Woods, have offered a libertarian interpretation of the crisis which differs from the explanations centered on deregulation and government oversight.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Ron Paul's book, *End the Fed,* Paul argues that the Federal Reserve's prolonged policy of artificially low interest rates in the early 2000s created a credit bubble that allowed for speculative investments and unsustainable levels of debt, particularly in housing.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Tom Woods' book *Meltdown*, he also contends that Federal Reserve manipulation of the money supply and credit markets distorted normal price signals, leading to widespread malinvestment, resulting in an inevitable correction.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Paul and Woods also criticized Fannie Mae's and Freddie Mac's role in the crisis, asserting that the entities engaged in excessive risk-taking by expanding homeownership beyond sustainable levels.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In doing this, the government intervention created moral hazard by assuring large financial institutions that they would receive government support in times of crisis, which Paul and Woods believe encouraged riskier behavior.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 1998 book, John McMurtry suggested that a financial crisis is a systemic crisis of capitalism itself.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his 1978 book, *The Downfall of Capitalism and Communism*, Ravi Batra suggests that growing inequality of financial capitalism produces speculative bubbles that burst and result in depression and major political changes.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also suggested that a "demand gap" related to differing wage and productivity growth explains deficit and debt dynamics important to stock market developments.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] John Bellamy Foster, a political economy analyst and editor of the *Monthly Review*, believed that the decrease in GDP growth rates since the early 1970s is due to increasing market saturation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Marxian economics followers Andrew Kliman, Michael Roberts, and Guglielmo Carchedi, in contradistinction to the *Monthly Review* school represented by Foster, pointed to capitalism's long-term tendency of the rate of profit to fall as the underlying cause of crises generally.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From this point of view, the problem was the inability of capital to grow or accumulate at sufficient rates through productive investment alone.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Low rates of profit in productive sectors led to speculative investment in riskier assets, where there was potential for greater return on investment.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The speculative frenzy of the late 1990s and 2000s was, in this view, a consequence of a rising organic composition of capital, expressed through the fall in the rate of profit.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to Michael Roberts, the fall in the rate of profit "eventually triggered the credit crunch of 2007 when credit could no longer support profits".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005 book, *The Battle for the Soul of Capitalism*, John C.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Bogle wrote that "Corporate America went astray largely because the power of managers went virtually unchecked by our gatekeepers for far too long".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his book *The Big Mo*, Mark Roeder, a former executive at the Swiss-based UBS Bank, suggested that large-scale momentum, or The Big Mo, "played a pivotal role" in the financial crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Roeder suggested that "recent technological advances, such as computer-driven trading programs, together with the increasingly interconnected nature of markets, has magnified the momentum effect.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Robert Reich attributed the economic downturn to the stagnation of wages in the United States, particularly those of the hourly workers who comprise 80% of the workforce.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This stagnation forced the population to borrow to meet the cost of living.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists Ailsa McKay and Margunn Bjørnholt argued that the financial crisis and the response to it revealed a crisis of ideas in mainstream economics and within the economics profession, and call for a reshaping of both the economy, economic theory and the economics profession.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A report by the International Labour Organization concluded that cooperative banking institutions were less likely to fail than their competitors during the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cooperative banking sector had 20% market share of the European banking sector, but accounted for only 7% of all the write-downs and losses between the third quarter of 2007 and first quarter of 2011.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2008, in the U.S., the rate of commercial bank failures was almost triple that of credit unions, and almost five times the credit union rate in 2010.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Credit unions increased their lending to small- and medium-sized businesses while overall lending to those businesses decreased.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists, particularly followers of mainstream economics, mostly failed to predict the crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several followers of heterodox economics predicted the crisis, with varying arguments.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dirk Bezemer credits 12 economists with predicting the crisis: Dean Baker, Wynne Godley, Fred Harrison, Michael Hudson, Eric Janszen, Med Jones, Steve Keen, Jakob Broechner Madsen & Jens Kjaer Sørensen, Kurt Richebächer, Nouriel Roubini, Peter Schiff, and Robert Shiller.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Shiller, a founder of the Case–Shiller index that measures home prices, wrote an article a year before the collapse of Lehman Brothers in which he predicted that a slowing U.S. housing market would cause the housing bubble to burst, leading to financial collapse.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Peter Schiff regularly appeared on television in the years before the crisis and warned of the impending real estate collapse.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Austrian School regarded the crisis as a vindication and classic example of a predictable credit-fueled bubble caused by laxity in monetary supply.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There were other economists that did warn of a pending crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The former Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, Raghuram Rajan, had predicted the crisis in 2005 when he became chief economist at the International Monetary Fund.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005, at a celebration honoring Alan Greenspan, who was about to retire as chairman of the US Federal Reserve, Rajan delivered a controversial paper that was critical of the financial sector.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In that paper, Rajan "argued that disaster might loom".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Rajan argued that financial sector managers were encouraged to "take risks that generate severe adverse consequences with small probability but, in return, offer generous compensation the rest of the time.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also took action against the establishment view by making a big financial bet on banking stocks and making a fortune from the crisis ("They didn't listen, so I took their money").
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Popular articles published in the mass media have led the general public to believe that the majority of economists have failed in their obligation to predict the financial crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, an article in *The New York Times* noted that economist Nouriel Roubini warned of such crisis as early as September 2006, and stated that the profession of economics is bad at predicting recessions.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to *The Guardian*, Roubini was ridiculed for predicting a collapse of the housing market and worldwide recession, while *The New York Times* labelled him "Dr.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 2012 article in the journal *Japan and the World Economy*, Andrew K.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Spiegel used a Multiple Indicator Multiple Cause (MIMIC) model on a cross-section of 107 countries to evaluate potential causes of the 2008 crisis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The authors examined various economic indicators, ignoring contagion effects across countries.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the fact that we use a wide number of possible causes in a flexible statistical framework, we are unable to link most of the commonly cited causes of the crisis to its incidence across countries.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The first visible institution to run into trouble in the United States was the Southern California–based IndyMac, a spin-off of Countrywide Financial.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Before its failure, IndyMac Bank was the largest savings and loan association in the Los Angeles market and the seventh-largest mortgage loan originator in the United States.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The failure of IndyMac Bank on July 11, 2008, was (until the crisis precipitated even larger failures) the fourth-largest bank failure in United States history, and the second-largest failure of a regulated thrift.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank's parent corporation was IndyMac Bancorp until the FDIC seized IndyMac Bank.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy in July 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank was founded as Countrywide Mortgage Investment in 1985 by David S.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Loeb and Angelo Mozilo as a means of collateralizing Countrywide Financial loans too big to be sold to Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1997, Countrywide spun off IndyMac as an independent company run by Mike Perry, who remained its CEO until the downfall of the bank in July 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The primary causes of its failure were largely associated with its business strategy of originating and securitizing Alt-A loans on a large scale.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This strategy resulted in rapid growth and a high concentration of risky assets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From its inception as a savings association in 2000, IndyMac grew to the seventh largest savings and loan and ninth largest originator of mortgage loans in the United States.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] During 2006, IndyMac originated over $90 billion (~$134 billion in 2024) of mortgages.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac often made loans without verification of the borrower's income or assets, and to borrowers with poor credit histories.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Appraisals obtained by IndyMac on underlying collateral were often questionable as well.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As an Alt-A lender, IndyMac's business model was to offer loan products to fit the borrower's needs, using an extensive array of risky option-adjustable-rate mortgages (option ARMs), subprime loans, 80/20 loans, and other nontraditional products.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Ultimately, loans were made to many borrowers who simply could not afford to make their payments.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The thrift remained profitable only as long as it was able to sell those loans in the secondary mortgage market.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac resisted efforts to regulate its involvement in those loans or tighten their issuing criteria: see the comment by Ruthann Melbourne, Chief Risk Officer, to the regulating agencies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On May 12, 2008, in the "Capital" section of its last 10-Q, IndyMac revealed that it may not be well capitalized in the future.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that during April 2008, Moody's and Standard & Poor's downgraded the ratings on a significant number of Mortgage-backed security (MBS) bonds—including $160 million (~$228 million in 2024) issued by IndyMac that the bank retained in its MBS portfolio.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac concluded that these downgrades would have harmed its risk-based capital ratio as of June 30, 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Had these lowered ratings been in effect on March 31, 2008, IndyMac concluded that the bank's capital ratio would have been 9.27% total risk-based.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac warned that if its regulators found its capital position to have fallen below "well capitalized" (minimum 10% risk-based capital ratio) to "adequately capitalized" (8–10% risk-based capital ratio) the bank might no longer be able to use brokered deposits as a source of funds.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Senator Charles Schumer (D-NY) later pointed out that brokered deposits made up more than 37% of IndyMac's total deposits, and asked the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) whether it had considered ordering IndyMac to reduce its reliance on these deposits.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $18.9 billion in total deposits reported on March 31, Senator Schumer would have been referring to a little over $7 billion in brokered deposits.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the breakout of maturities of these deposits is not known exactly, a simple averaging would have put the threat of brokered deposits loss to IndyMac at $500 million a month, had the regulator disallowed IndyMac from acquiring new brokered deposits on June 30.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac was taking new measures to preserve capital, such as deferring interest payments on some preferred securities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dividends on common shares had already been suspended for the first quarter of 2008, after being cut in half the previous quarter.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The company still had not secured a significant capital infusion nor found a ready buyer.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that the bank's risk-based capital was only $47 million above the minimum required for this 10% mark.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] But it did not reveal some of that $47 million (~$67 million in 2024) capital it claimed it had, as of March 31, 2008, was fabricated.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] When home prices declined in the latter half of 2007 and the secondary mortgage market collapsed, IndyMac was forced to hold $10.7 billion (~$15.5 billion in 2024) of loans it could not sell in the secondary market.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Its reduced liquidity was further exacerbated in late June 2008 when account holders withdrew $1.55 billion (~$2.21 billion in 2024) or about 7.5% of IndyMac's deposits.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This bank run on the thrift followed the public release of a letter from Senator Charles Schumer to the FDIC and OTS.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The letter outlined the Senator's concerns with IndyMac.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the run was a contributing factor in the timing of IndyMac's demise, the underlying cause of the failure was the unsafe and unsound way it was operated.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac announced the closure of both its retail lending and wholesale divisions, halted new loan submissions, and cut 3,800 jobs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On July 11, 2008, citing liquidity concerns, the FDIC put IndyMac Bank into conservatorship.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A bridge bank, IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB, was established to assume control of IndyMac Bank's assets, its secured liabilities, and its insured deposit accounts.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC announced plans to open IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB on July 14, 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Until then, depositors would have access to their insured deposits through ATMs, their existing checks, and their existing debit cards.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Telephone and Internet account access was restored when the bank reopened.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC guarantees the funds of all insured accounts up to US$100,000, and declared a special advance dividend to the roughly 10,000 depositors with funds in excess of the insured amount, guaranteeing 50% of any amounts in excess of $100,000.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Yet, even with the pending sale of Indymac to IMB Management Holdings, an estimated 10,000 uninsured depositors of Indymac are still at a loss of over $270 million.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $32 billion in assets, IndyMac Bank was one of the largest bank failures in American history.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy on July 31, 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Initially the companies affected were those directly involved in home construction and mortgage lending such as Northern Rock and Countrywide Financial, as they could no longer obtain financing through the credit markets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Over 100 mortgage lenders went bankrupt during 2007 and 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Concerns that investment bank Bear Stearns would collapse in March 2008 resulted in its fire-sale to JP Morgan Chase.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The financial institution crisis hit its peak in September and October 2008.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several major institutions either failed, were acquired under duress, or were subject to government takeover.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These included Lehman Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, Washington Mutual, Wachovia, Citigroup, and AIG.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On October 6, 2008, three weeks after Lehman Brothers filed the largest bankruptcy in U.S. history, Lehman's former CEO Richard S.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld Jr. found himself before Representative Henry A.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Waxman, the California Democrat who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld said he was a victim of the collapse, blaming a "crisis of confidence" in the markets for dooming his firm.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] In its earliest usage, *alma mater* was an honorific title for various mother goddesses, especially Ceres or Cybele.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] Later, in Catholicism, it became a title for Mary, mother of Jesus.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] By the early 17th century, the nursing mother became an allegory for universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] Used by many schools in Europe and North America, it has special association with the University of Bologna, whose motto *Alma Mater Studiorum* ("nurturing mother of studies") emphasizes its role in originating the modern university.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] Several university campuses in North America display artistic representations of *Alma Mater*, depicted as a robed woman wearing a laurel wreath crown.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] The earliest and of these is the bronze *Alma Mater* statue at Columbia University, designed in 1901 by Daniel Chester French.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] In the US the term *alma mater* is often used to describe a school song.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] Although *alma* (nourishing) was a common epithet for Ceres, Cybele, Venus, and other mother goddesses, it was not frequently used in conjunction with *mater* in classical Latin.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] After the fall of Rome, the term was used in Christian liturgy to describe Jesus' mother, Mary.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] "Alma Redemptoris Mater" is a well-known eleventh century antiphon devoted to Mary.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] The earliest documented use of the term to refer to a university is in 1600, when the University of Cambridge printer, John Legate, began using an emblem for the university press.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] The first-known appearance of the device is in William Perkins', *A Golden Chain*, a book first printed by Legate in 1600.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] On the title-page, the Latin phrase *Alma Mater Cantabrigia* ("nourishing mother Cambridge") is inscribed on a pedestal bearing a lactating woman wearing a mural crown.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] In reference works of English etymology, often the first university-related usage is cited as 1710, when an academic mother figure is mentioned in a remembrance of Henry More by Richard Ward.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] Many historic European universities have adopted *Alma Mater* as part of the Latin translation of their official name.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] The Latin name of the University of Bologna, *Alma Mater Studiorum* (nourishing mother of studies), refers to its status as the oldest continuously operating university in the world.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] At other European universities, such as the Alma Mater Lipsiensis in Leipzig, Germany, or Alma Mater Jagiellonica, Poland, the title emphasizes historic ties to a founding city or dynasty.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] The Alma Mater Europaea in Salzburg, Austria, an international university founded by the European Academy of Sciences and Arts in 2010, uses the term as its official name.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] In the United States, the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, has been called the "Alma Mater of the Nation" because of its ties to the founding of the country.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] At Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario, and the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia, the main student government is known as the Alma Mater Society.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] Sculptures of *Alma Mater* are found on several North American university campuses.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] In 1901, to commemorate the opening of the Low Library, Columbia University commissioned Daniel Chester French to design a bronze statue for the library's steps.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] French chose the *Alma Mater* to allegorically embody the university without depicting its founder, King George II.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] A similar sculpture, cast in 1919 by Mario Korbel, sits on the main entrance steps at the University of Havana.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] Other tributes to *Alma Mater* include Lorado Taft's *1929 sculpture* at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and Cyrus Dallin's 1925 sculpture at the Mary Institute in 1925, commissioned by Washington University supporters.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/alma-mater] An altarpiece mural in Yale University's Sterling Memorial Library, painted in 1932 by Eugene Savage, depicts the *Alma Mater* as a bearer of light and truth, standing in the midst of figures representing the arts and sciences.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] The company name was changed from **Hitachi Astemo, Ltd.** to Astemo, Ltd. on April 1, 2025.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Astemo was established in January 2021 as a global automotive components manufacturer through the business merger of Hitachi Automotive Systems, Keihin Corporation, Showa Corporation, and Nissin Kogyo.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] The name "Astemo" stands for "Advanced Sustainable Technologies for Mobility", reflecting the company's focus on technologies related to connected, autonomous, shared and electric mobility.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Astemo develops automotive technologies aligned with the industry trends of connectivity, autonomous systems and electrification, with a focus on both passenger and motorcycle applications.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Astemo's ownership structure includes major stakes from both Hitachi, Ltd. and Honda Motor Co., Ltd., each holding 40%, with JIC Capital holding the remaining 20%.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] While Astemo includes former Honda-affiliated parts manufacturers, it also maintains business relationships with Nissan Motor Co., reflecting Hitachi's historical ties to the Nissan Group.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] In December 2025, Honda announced it would acquire an additional 21% of Astemo shares from Hitachi.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] As a result, the shareholding structure of Astemo will change to 61% for Honda, 20% for JIC, and 19% for Hitachi.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Astemo has expanded its research and development activities in electric powertrains, advanced driver-assistance systems, and in-vehicle software.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] These efforts support its strategic focus on electrification and autonomous mobility.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] The company has also pursued partnerships and vertical integration to address industry competition and supply chain challenges.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] In December 2024, the Government of Cantabria awarded the Hitachi Astemo Buelna plant a €1 million grant through SODERCAN’s competitive programme for major industrial competitiveness projects.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] The funding supports a €5 million experimental development project focused on advanced braking systems, to be completed over 18 months.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] This initiative underlines the region’s strategic support for automotive innovation and sustainability efforts.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Astemo develops components for electric and autonomous vehicles, with a focus on integration of key systems such as power control units, motors, inverters, and software-defined vehicle platforms.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] The company also emphasizes model-based systems engineering and virtual validation to shorten development timelines and reduce prototyping costs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] In 2023, Astemo announced a ¥15.3 billion (~US $100 million) expansion of its Berea, Kentucky plant to support its electrification business.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] In July 2025, Astemo announced a £100 million investment in its Horwich manufacturing facility in Bolton, Greater Manchester.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] The project will establish a new production line dedicated to electric vehicle (EV) inverters, making the site the only facility in the United Kingdom with this production capability.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] As of 2025, Astemo operates over 100 business sites globally, including manufacturing plants, R&D centers and regional offices across Asia, Europe and the Americas.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Astemo's facilities span over 25 countries, including sites in Mexico, France, Brazil, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] A complete list is available on the Astemo Global Network.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] In September 2025, *CBS News* and *The Detroit News* reported that Astemo planned to establish a regional headquarters in Wixom, Michigan, as part of a $95 million investment expected to create about 200 jobs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Hitachi Astemo sponsors Team Penske in NTT IndyCar Series in the U.S.A.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Astemo also sponsors Real Racing in the Super GT GT500 class and S.I.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] RACING in the MFJ All Japan Road Race Championship Series.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Astemo owns the Japanese women's volleyball team "Hitachi Astemo Rivale" and sponsors Mie Honda Heat, a Japanese rugby union team based in Suzuka City.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] On December 21, 2021, Hitachi Astemo admitted to falsifying inspection data on brake and suspension components.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/astemo] Over 50,000 instances of improper testing were identified, dating back to 2003.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] The two most common bachelor's degrees are the Bachelor of Arts (BA) and the Bachelor of Science (BS or BSc).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] In countries with qualifications frameworks, bachelor's degrees are normally one of the major levels in the framework (sometimes two levels where non-honours and honours bachelor's degrees are considered separately).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] However, some qualifications titled bachelor's degree may be at other levels (e.g., MBBS) and some qualifications with non-bachelor's titles may be classified as bachelor's degrees (e.g. the Scottish MA and Canadian MD).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] The term *bachelor* in the 12th century referred to a knight bachelor, who was too young or poor to gather vassals under his own banner.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] By the end of the 13th century, it was also used by junior members of guilds or universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] By folk etymology or wordplay, the word *baccalaureus* came to be associated with *bacca lauri* ("laurel berry"); this is in reference to laurels being awarded for academic success or honours.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] An honours degree generally requires a higher academic standard than a pass degree, and in some systems an additional year of study beyond the non-honours bachelor's.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] Some countries, such as Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and Canada, have a postgraduate "bachelor with honours" degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] This may be taken as a consecutive academic degree, continuing on from the completion of a bachelor's degree program in the same field, or as part of an integrated honours program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] Programs like these typically require completion of a full year-long research thesis project.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] The map shows how long it takes for students in different countries to get a bachelor's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p01] It generally takes between 3 and 6 years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In most African countries, the university systems follow the model of their former colonizing power.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] For example, the Nigerian university system is similar to the British system, while the Ivorian system is akin to the French.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The degree is typically identical to the program of France's universities, as specified in the LMD reform.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degree programs cover most of the fields in Algerian universities, except some fields, such as Medicine and Pharmaceutical Science.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees at the University of Botswana normally take four years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The system draws on both British and American models.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Degrees are classified as First Class, Second Class Division One (2:1), Second Class Division Two (2:2) and Third as in English degrees, but without being described as honours.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The main degrees are named by British tradition (Arts, Science, Law, etc.); in recent years, however, there have been a number of degrees named after specific subjects, such as Bachelor of Library and Information.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Kenya, university education is supported by the government.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A bachelor's degree is awarded to students who successfully complete a three to seven-year course depending on the area of study.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] For most degree programs, a research project and an internship period after which a report is written by the student is a must before the student is allowed to graduate.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In 2012, a number of select colleges were upgraded to university status in a bid to increase the intake of students into degree programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Morocco, a bachelor's degree is referred to as *al-ʾijāzah* (Arabic, French: **licence**).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The course of study takes three years, which are further divided into two cycles.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The first cycle comprises the first, or propaedeutic, year.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] After successfully completing their first two years, students can pursue either theoretical specialization (**études fondamentales**) or professional specialization (**études professionnelles**).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The second cycle is one year after whose completion students receive the **licence d'études fondamentales** or the *l*icence professionnelle**.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This academic degree system was introduced in September 2003.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] University admission is extremely competitive, with attendant advantages and disadvantages.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Nonetheless, it takes four to five years to complete a bachelor's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In cases of poor performance, the time limit is double the standard amount of time.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] For example, one may not study for more than 10 years for a five-year course.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Students are normally asked to leave if they must take longer.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Nigerian universities offer BSc, BTech (usually from Universities of Technology), BArch (six years), and other specialized undergraduate degrees, such as BEng.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Science undergraduate degrees may require six months or a semester dedicated to SIWES (Students Industrial Work Experience Scheme) but it is usually mandatory for all engineering degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A semester for project work/thesis is required, not excluding course work, during the bachelor thesis in the final year.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The classifications of degrees: first-class, second-class (upper and lower), third-class (with honours; i.e., BSc (Hons)) and a pass (no honours).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] First- and second-class graduates are immediately eligible for advanced postgraduate degrees (i.e., MSc and PhD), but other classes may be required for an additional postgraduate diploma before such eligibility.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Furthermore, all graduating students are obliged to do the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC) requirement, which usually takes one year, after which they are eligible to pursue higher degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The NYSC is a paramilitary service that involves students' being posted to different parts of the country to serve in various capacities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Principal objectives of the NYSC are to forge national cohesion, encourage students to apply their obtained knowledge to solving problems of rural Nigeria, and others.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The NYSC was established by law after the Nigerian Civil War.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Polytechnical schools (polytechnics) in Nigeria are not considered universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] They are mandated to educate technicians of high calibre; they offer the OND (ordinary national diploma) and the HND (higher national diploma).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The polytechnics focus very strongly on practical technical training.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The BSc and HND are compared in engineering circles, but there are significant differences in training philosophies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Honours degrees in Nigeria are differentiated only on the basis of performance.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Honours degrees include the first-class degree, second-class degrees (upper and lower) and the third-class degree, but not the pass.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All university students must do an independent research project which applies the knowledge obtained during the previous years of study.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The project work must be submitted in the semester before graduation and usually takes a significant number of points.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Further course work is not precluded during the project work, but the courses are fewer and are at an advanced level.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Project work is orally defended before the faculty and before peers.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the sciences and engineering a demonstration of the project is usually required.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In South Africa, an honours degree is an additional postgraduate qualification in the same area as the undergraduate major, and requires at least one further year of study as well as a research report.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Most universities in Tunisia offer the 3-year bachelor's degree, except some fields, which are Medicine, Pharmacy, Engineering, Architecture and Bachelor of Science in Business Administration, solely offered by Tunis Business School and lasts 4 years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The region typically confers associates, bachelor's, master's, doctoral, and postdoctoral degrees to graduating students.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] University education in Argentina is currently regulated by the Ministry of Human Capital, with the requirements of a Licenciatura or bachelor's degree, also referred to as a university degree program lasting 4, 5, or more years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] These programs can be equivalent to professional degrees, such as law, medicine, engineering, psychology, education, arts, architecture, industrial design, or bachelor's degrees more oriented towards research and teaching in a specific field of science.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The undergraduate degrees recognized by the Higher Education Law (LES) are programs that must have more than 2,600 hours of instruction, under the guidance of the National Commission for University Evaluation and Accreditation (CONEAU).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The current regulations govern the Institutional Distance Education System, Ministerial Resolution No.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] 2641-E/2017 and Ministerial Resolution No.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] There is no distinction between universities and non-university institutions, such as teacher training colleges.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Brazil, a bachelor's degree takes from three years to six years to complete depending on the course load and the program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A bachelor's degree is the title sought by Brazilians in order to be a professional in a certain area of human knowledge.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Master's and doctoral degrees are additional degrees for those seeking an academic career or a specific understanding of a field.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Even without a formal adhesion to the Bologna system, a Brazilian "bachelor's" would correspond to a European "first cycle".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Depending on programs and personal choices, Europeans can achieve a master's degree in as little as four years (a three-year bachelor's and a one-year master's) and as long as six years (a four-year bachelor's, a two-year master's) of higher education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Education in Canada is governed independently by each province and territory; however, a common framework for degrees was agreed to by the Council of Ministers of Education, Canada, in 2007.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This adopted descriptors for bachelor's, master's and doctoral degrees that were deliberately similar to those defined by the Bologna Process.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This last category includes graduate-entry degrees titled as if they were doctorates, such as MD, JD and DDS degrees—despite their names, these are considered bachelor's degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees may take either three or four years to complete and are awarded by colleges and universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In many universities and colleges, bachelor's degrees are differentiated either as (ordinary) bachelor's or as honours bachelor's degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The term "honours" is an academic distinction, which indicates that students must achieve their bachelor's degree with a sufficiently high overall grade point average; in addition, some programs may require more education than non-honours programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The honours degrees are sometimes designated with the abbreviation in brackets of "(Hon(s))".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Going back in history, the *Bachelor with Honours* (Latin *baccalaureatus cum honore*, French: *baccalauréat spécialisé*) was traditionally taken as the highest undergraduate degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The program requires at least 4 years of studies, with strong emphasis on the research-based *Honours Seminar Thesis* which is considered approximately equivalent to a formal master's thesis.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Universities show the academic degree as well as the possible honours distinction (Latin honours) on the diploma (e.g., "*BACCALAUREATUS ARTIUM CUM HONORE ...
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Quebec, students have to take a minimum of two years of college before entering, for example, a three-year Bachelor of Science (BSc) or a four-year Bachelor of Engineering (BEng) program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the province of Ontario, the most bachelor's degrees offered by Ontario universities are academic in nature.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In contrast, Ontario legislation requires bachelor's degrees offered by Ontario colleges to be applied and vocationally focused.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Currently, the trend is for universities not to offer a bachelor's degree and to offer instead a licentiate's or "*ingeniero*" degree after five years of education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees may take an average of five years (from four to five years) to complete depending on the course load and the program, they are awarded by colleges and universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Each college has its own curriculum and requirements with an emphasis of their choice, governed independently by each state of the republic.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] After finishing all the subjects the student require a final work, which means the completion of particular honours seminars, research and development or a written thesis in a particular field.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This requirement takes about six months to one year depending on the type of degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degree should not be falsely related with its Spanish cognate "bachiller", which designate a prerequisite for matriculate in a career or bachelor studies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The official name for a bachelor's degree in Mexico is "licenciado" and such studies are referred as "licenciatura".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees should not be confused with Engineering Degrees, where an *Ingeniería* is prefixed to the name and requires additional courses for certification as an Engineer.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Those students are awarded the same bachelor's degree as students completing the standard curriculum but with the notation *in cursu honorum* on the transcript and the diploma.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Usually, the above Latin honours are separate from the notation for this honours course, but a student in the honours course generally must maintain grades worthy of at least the *cum laude* notation anyway.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Hence, a graduate might receive a diploma *Artium Baccalaureatum rite* or *Artium Baccalaureatum summa cum laude* in the regular course or *Artium Baccalaureatum summa cum laude in cursu honorum* in the honours course.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] If the student has completed the requirements for an honours degree only in a particular discipline (e.g., English language and literature), the degree is designated accordingly (e.g., "BA with Honours in English").
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In this case, the degree candidate will complete the normal curriculum for all subjects except the selected discipline ("English", in the preceding example).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The requirements in either case usually require completion of particular honours seminars, independent research at a level higher than usually required (often with greater personal supervision by faculty than usual), and a written honours thesis in the major subject.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Requirements for such notations of honours generally include minimum grade point averages (GPA), with the highest average required for the *summa* distinction (or *maxima*, when that distinction is present).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Six notable exceptions are Reed College, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, The Evergreen State College, Sarah Lawrence College, Bard College, and Bennington College, which do not have deans' lists, Latin honours recognitions, or undergraduate honours programs or subjects.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Starting in 2023, some colleges and universities began offering three-year bachelor's programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] As of late 2025, 70 institutions had the programs or planned to.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A three-year degree could be obtained with additional credits during the regular school year and summer courses.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Most reduced the number of required credits, identifying the program as "accelerated pathways" on the transcript.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Reasons for choosing a three-year program include the increasing cost of education, and the desire of students not to take courses they did not need.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Engineering universities provide four-year degree programs for bachelor's degree courses of study (BSc in Eng and BSc).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Medical colleges have five-year degree programmes (MBBS, BDS).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In law education there is a two-year LLB degree after completing three years in a BA program for a total of five years of study.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] There is also a four-year LLB honours degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The Bachelor of Architecture (BArch) and Bachelor of Pharmacy (BPharm) are professional degrees awarded to students who complete a five-year course of study in the field at some universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All of these programs begin after achieving the Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC – in total 12 years of school education).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] There are 13 kinds of *statutory* bachelor's degrees in China: Bachelor of Philosophy, Economics, Laws, Education, Arts, History, Science, Engineering, Agriculture, Medicine, Management, Military Science, and Fine Arts.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Since the undergraduate education system in China is modeled after its American counterpart, all of the degrees are adapted from those of the United States except for the issuing of the degree certificate.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Once a student has fulfilled their course requirements, a "graduate certificate" will be given.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In order to get the degree, a student must finish and pass the dissertation stage; only then will they be awarded a degree certified by the Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Most bachelor's degree in China needs four years to complete, with the exception that the Bachelor of Medicine degree requires five years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Any Chinese citizen can also get a bachelor's degree via the undergraduate majors of the Self-Taught Higher Education Examinations (Chinese: 高等教育自学考试).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Indonesia, most of the current bachelor's degrees are domain-specific degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Therefore, there are more than 20 bachelor's degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The historical situation in Austria was very similar to that in Germany, with the traditional first degrees being the *magister* and the *diplom*, which are master's-level qualifications.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] From 2004, bachelor's degrees have been reintroduced as part of the Bologna Process reforms.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] These can be studied at universities, leading to a bachelor's degree (BA or BSc) after three or four years, and at Fachhochschulen (universities of applied science), leading to a *bachelor (FH)* after three years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Education in Belgium is run by the language communities, with separate higher education systems being administered by the Flemish Community and the French Community.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Both systems have been reformed to align with the Bologna Process, the Flemish Community from 2003 and the French Community from 2004.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the Flemish Community, bachelor's degrees may be either academic or professional.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] These degrees last three years, and may be followed in both cases by an advanced bachelor diploma (French: *Bachelier de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] 'Specialized Bachelor'; Dutch: *Bachelor-na-bachelor*, lit.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] 'Bachelor-after-bachelor'), lasting one year (cf. the Australian bachelor honours degree).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All of these qualifications are at level 6 on the EQF, to which the Flemish Qualification Framework was referenced in June 2011.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the French Community, universities award *grade de bachelier* (3 years) as the equivalent of bachelor's degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Outside of universities, professional programs may be *type long* (long type) or *type court* (short type), both of which are offered at *hautes ecoles* and *ecoles supérieures des arts*.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The long type takes in a *grade de bachelier (type long)* (3 years), which is followed by a *master* degree (1 or 2 years), while the short type has a *grade de bachelier professionnalisant (type court)* (3 years), which may be followed by a *bachelier de spécialisation* (1 year).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All *bachelier* degrees (including the *bachelier de spécialisation*) are equivalent to level 6 of the EQF, but have not been formally referenced.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Most public universities and community colleges in Croatia today offer a three-year bachelor program, which can be followed up typically with a two-year master's (graduate) program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All bachelor's degrees in Croatia are professional.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] For distinction, in universities the title is "univ. bacc." (university bachelor) and in community colleges is just "bacc.".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Zagreb School of Economics and Management has a four-year bachelor's program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Academies that specialize in the arts, e.g. the Academy of Fine Arts in Zagreb, have four-year bachelor's programs followed by a one-year master's.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Higher education in Cyprus is aligned with the Bologna Process and governed by the *Cyprus Agency of Quality Assurance and Accreditation in Higher Education* (CYQAA).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees at Cypriot universities are four years in duration, corresponding to 240 ECTS credits.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Public universities in Cyprus comprise the University of Cyprus, the Cyprus University of Technology and the Open University of Cyprus, all of which admit students through the annual Pancyprian Examinations.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Private universities, including the European University Cyprus and the University of Nicosia, admit students on the basis of academic records and offer programs in Greek and English.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Historically, the baccalaureus was the undergraduate degree awarded to students who graduated from the course of trivium (grammar, dialectic and rhetoric) at a faculty of liberal arts (either at the Charles University or at the University of Olomouc).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] It was a necessary prerequisite to continue either with the faculty of liberal arts (quadrivium leading to a master's degree and further to a doctoral degree) or to study at one of the other three historical faculties—law, medicine or theology.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A bachelor's degree, abbreviated BcA, in the field of fine arts, and Bc (*Bakalář* in Czech) in other fields is awarded for accredited undergraduate programs at universities and colleges.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The vast majority of undergraduate programmes offered in the Czech Republic have a standard duration of three years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the Czech tertiary education system, most universities and colleges today offer a three-year bachelor program, which can be followed up typically with a two-year master's (graduate) program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Some specializations, such as doctors of medicine and veterinary doctors, hold exceptions from the general system in that the only option is a six-year master's program with no bachelor stage (graduate with title doctor).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This is due mainly to the difficulty of meaningfully splitting up the education for these specialisations.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The bachelor's degree was re-introduced at universities in Denmark in 1993, after the original degree (baccalaureus) was abandoned in 1775.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The bachelor's degree is awarded after three or four years of study at a university and follows a scheme quite similar to the British one.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] However, both in the business and the academic world in Denmark, the bachelor's degree is still considered to be "the first half" of a master's (candidatus).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is often not considered a degree in its own right, despite the politicians' best attempts to make it more accepted.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The bachelor's degree has also been used since the late 1990s in a number of areas like nursing and teaching.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Usually referred to as a "professional bachelor" (Danish: *professionsbachelor*), these degrees usually require 3 to 4+1⁄2 years of combined theoretical and practical study at a "professional university college" (Danish: *professionshøjskole*) or "business academy" (Danish: "erhvervsakademier").
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These professional bachelor's degrees do grant access to some university master's program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These professional bachelor's degrees are considered to be a full education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The traditional bachelor's degree is the equivalent of the French *Licence* three-year degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Since the new European system of 2004 LMD Bologna process was founded, it has become standard to recognize a bachelor's degree over three years with a *licence* degree, a master's degree over five years, and a doctorate over eight years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some private institutions are however literally naming their degrees *bachelor.* Some of these *bachelor* are "*Diplômes visés*" (often delivered by specialized private schools, such as business, design, film or journalism schools), others are "*Diplômes certifiés*" by the French State.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The others are not accredited by the French State.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Historically, the bachelor's degree, called "*Bakkalaureus*", existed in Germany since the late Middle Ages.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] But it was abolished by the educational reforms undertaken in 1820.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The Abitur degree – the final degree received in school after a specialized 'college phase' of two years – replaced it, and universities only awarded graduate degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The magister degree, a graduate degree, was awarded after five years of study.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In 1899, a second graduate degree, the diplom, was introduced when the *Technische Hochschulen* (TH) received university status.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] With the introduction of the universities of applied sciences, a shortened version of the latter, referred to as *Diplom (FH)* and designed to take three to four years, was phased in between 1969 and 1972.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] However, in 1998, in order to comply with the European *Bologna process*, a new educational law reintroduced the bachelor's degree (first degree after three years of study) in Germany.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Today, these degrees can be called either "*Bakkalaureus*" or "bachelor" (in accordance with federal law), but the English term is more common.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] According to the Bologna model, the bachelor is followed by the post-graduate master's degree of another two years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The traditional degrees of diplom and magister were mostly abolished in 2010, although the diplom still persists in a few subjects and universities and has been reintroduced as alternative degree in some places.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The traditional degrees have been re-mapped to the new European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) point system to make them comparable to the new bachelor's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The Greek bachelor's degree is called πτυχίο (transliterated to "ptychio"; Greek: πτυχίο; ptychio in dhimotiki from 1976–present; or defunct πτυχίον; ptychion in polytonic, katharevousa up until 1976).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is earned after four to six years of undergraduate studies, depending on the field, and is a first cycle qualification in the Bologna Process with 240 or more ECTS credits.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is placed at level 6 of the national qualifications framework of Greece which is officially named Hellenic Qualification Framework (HQF), which is referenced to level 6 of the European Qualifications Framework.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is classified as a level 6 qualification in the ISCED.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The bachelor's degree is provided by all Higher Education Institutions (HEIs), including universities, specialist HEIs, formerly technological educational institutes (TEIs) (1983–2019).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In 1995, it changed TEI six-semester-mode of undergraduate degree programme of studies legally equivalent to an ordinary bachelor's degree (Ord) (3+1⁄2-year; 210 ECTS, 1983–1995) into nine-semester-mode (4-year; 240 ECTS, 1995–2019).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Technical universities and some universities offer a five-year (300 ECTS) undergraduate programme leading to a Δίπλωμα (Greek) Diploma (integrated-master-level-granting, Master's degree equivalent) at Level 7 of the HQF.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In the classic, pre-Bologna educational system, Hungarian academic programs were not divided into bachelor's and master's degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] However, while an average university (Hungarian: *egyetem*) degree lasted 5 years, there were undergraduate college (Hungarian: *főiskola*) degrees obtainable, in either 3 or 4 years of length.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These diplomas are today considered to be equivalents of a BA/BSc (undergraduate college) or an MA/MSc (university) degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The Bologna System was introduced in 2005, and with the last classes graduating in 2009, it is the sole form of higher education in the country.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees (Hungarian: *alapképzés*, "basic degree") usually last 3 years, but there are degrees in certain areas of education – most notably engineering, economics, and some natural sciences – where an additional semester is required, lengthening the program to 3,5 years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In order to graduate, students must earn credits (ECTS) and write a thesis for which students have to elaborate on an argument under the supervision of a professor (generally from three to eight ECTS).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] According to each faculty internal ruling, a *lode* may be awarded to candidates with a 110/110 mark for recognition of the excellence of the final project.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the bachelor's degree was introduced in 2002 with the change of the Dutch degree system due to the European Bologna process.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Until that time, the Dutch universities did not have a Bachelor level degree (although the Candidate's diploma existed until 1982, which was more-or-less of the same level).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Prior to the Dutch degree system change a single program at the university comprised the same course load as the bachelor's and master's programs together which led to the doctorandus degree (or for legal studies to the "Meester in de rechten" and engineering to "Ingenieur").
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In 2002, with the introduction of the Bachelor's master's doctorate system, the single (4- or 5-year) program at Dutch universities has been changed and split into a 3-year program leading to the bachelor's degree and a subsequent a 1- or 2-year program leading to the master's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Those who had already started the doctorandus program could, upon completing it, opt for the doctorandus degree (before their name, abbreviated to 'drs.'), or simply use the master's degree (behind their name) in accordance with the new standard.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Since these graduates do not have a separate bachelor's degree (which is in fact – in retrospect – incorporated into the program), the master's degree is their first academic degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In 2003/2004, the Dutch degree system was changed because of the Bologna process.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] While the titles ing., bc., ir., mr., drs. and dr. are used before one's own name, the degrees B, M or D are mentioned after one's name.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is still allowed to use the traditional titles.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Whether a bachelor's degree is granted by a *hogeschool* or university is highly relevant since these parallel systems of higher education have traditionally served somewhat different purposes, with the vocational colleges mainly concentrating on skills and practical training.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A BA or BSc from a university grants "immediate" entry into a master's program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Moreover, this is usually considered a formality to allow students to switch to foreign universities master's programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Recently, HBO (vocational) master's degrees have been introduced in the Netherlands.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Graduates thereof may use neither the extension "of Arts" (MA) nor "of Science" (MSc).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] They may use an M followed by the field of specialization (e.g., MDes).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] This year of study to "convert" from the vocational to academic (WO – *wetenschappelijk onderwijs*, literally "scientific education") is also known as a "bridge" or "premasters" year.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Despite the use of the terminology "university of applied science" the higher vocational colleges are not considered to be "universities" within the Netherlands.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In February 2011, the Dutch State Secretary of Education decided to adhere to the recommendations written in a report by the Veerman Commission.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In the near future, the distinction between academic and higher vocational degrees will disappear.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In Spain, due to the ongoing transition to a model compliant with the Bologna agreement, exact equivalents to the typical Anglosphere bachelor's degree and master's degree are being implemented progressively.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The "título de grado" is now the prerequisite to access a master's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The "título de máster" is now the prerequisite to access doctoral studies, and its duration and the kind of institutions that can teach these programs are regulated in the framework of the European Higher Education Area.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Up until 2009/2010, the system was split into three categories of degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The official first-cycle degrees are comparable in terms of duration, scope, and educational outcomes to an Anglo-Saxon bachelor's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Meanwhile, the second-cycle degrees are comparable in terms of duration, scope, and educational outcomes to an Anglo-Saxon bachelor's + master's degrees combination if compared with the Anglo-Saxon system.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The bachelor's degree is the standard undergraduate degree in the United Kingdom, with the most common degrees being the Bachelor of Arts (BA) and Bachelor of Science (BSc).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Most bachelor's degree courses (apart from the very rare postgraduate awards, and those in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science) lead to honours degrees, with ordinary degrees generally only being awarded to those who do not meet the required pass mark for an honours degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] With the exception of the postgraduate bachelor's degrees and bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science, UK bachelor's degrees (whether honours or non-honours) are first cycle (end of cycle) qualifications under the Bologna Process.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Postgraduate bachelor's degrees and bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science are second cycle (end of cycle) qualifications.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science offer intercalated degrees en route to the final qualification.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees should not be confused with baccalaureate qualifications, which derive their name from the same root.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In the UK, baccalaureate qualifications, e.g.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] International Baccalaureate, Welsh Baccalaureate, English Baccalaureate, are gained at secondary schools rather than being degree-level qualifications.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Until the 19th century, a bachelor's degree represented the first degree in a particular faculty, with Arts representing undergraduate study, thus the Bachelor of Civil Law (BCL) at Oxford and the Bachelor of Laws (LLB) at Cambridge, for example, were postgraduate degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The same historical usage of indicating an undergraduate degree by it being in the faculty of arts rather than being a bachelor's degree gives rise to the Oxbridge MA and the Scottish MA).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In England, Wales and Northern Ireland, bachelor's degrees usually take three years of study to complete, although courses may take four years where they include a year abroad or a placement year.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Degrees may have titles related to their broad subject area or faculty, such as BA or BSc, or may be more subject specific (e.g.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The majority of bachelor's degrees are now honours degrees, although this has not always been the case historically.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Although first degree courses are usually three years (360 credits), direct second year entry is sometimes possible for students transferring from other courses or those who have completed foundation degrees, via accreditation of prior learning or more formal credit transfer arrangements.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some universities compress the three-year course into two years by teaching for a full calendar year (180 credits) rather than a standard academic year (120 credits), thus maintaining the full 360-credit extent of the course.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In addition to bachelor's degrees, some institutions offer integrated master's degrees as first degrees in some subjects (particularly in STEM fields).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These integrate teaching at bachelor's and master's level in a four-year (five-year if with industrial experience) course, which often shares the first two years with the equivalent bachelor's course.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The normal academic standard for bachelor's degrees in England, Wales and Northern Ireland is the *honours degree*.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some institutions have announced that they intend to replace this system of classifying honours degrees with an American-style Grade Point Average.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] An *ordinary* (or *unclassified*) degree, which only requires passes worth 300 credits rather than the 360 of the honours degree, may be awarded if a student has completed the full honours degree course but has not obtained sufficient passes to earn a degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Completion of just the first two years of the course can lead to a Diploma of Higher Education and completion of only the first year to a Certificate of Higher Education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] On the Framework for Higher Education Qualifications, standard undergraduate bachelor's degrees with and without honours are at level 6, although the courses include learning across levels 4 to 6.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Honours degrees normally require 360 credits with a minimum of 90 at level 6, while ordinary degrees need 300 credits with a minimum of 60 at level 6.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science are at level 7, with learning spanning levels 4 to 7, and are not normally credit rated.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The Diploma of Higher Education is a level 5 (second year of bachelor's degree) qualification and requires 240 credits, a minimum of 90 at level 5; The Certificate of Higher Education is a level 4 (first year of bachelor's degree) qualification and requires 120 credits, a minimum of 90 at level 4.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Honours degrees may be awarded as BA (Hons) or MA (Hons) in the arts and social sciences, or BSc (Hons) for sciences, or have more specific titles such as BEng.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] As in the rest of the UK, integrated master's degrees, taking five years in Scotland, are also offered as first degrees alongside bachelor's degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] An honours degree may be directly linked to professional or vocational qualifications, particularly in fields such as engineering, surveying and architecture.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These courses tend to have highly specified curricula, leaving students without many options for broader study.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Others, following a more traditional route, start off with a broad range of studies across the faculty that has admitted the student or, via modular study, across the whole university.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Students on these courses specialise later in their degree programmes.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Typically degree grades are based only on the final two years of study, after a specialisation has been chosen, so broader study courses taken in the first two years do not affect the final degree grade.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Honours degrees are subdivided into classes in the same way as the rest of the UK, depending on the overall grade achieved.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These are, from highest to lowest; first class, upper second class (2:1), lower second class (2:2), and third class.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Ordinary degrees are awarded to students who have completed three years at university studying a variety of related subjects.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These may be taken over a broad range of subjects or (as with honours degrees) with a specialisation in a particular subject (in the latter case, they are sometimes known as *designated degrees*).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] As ordinary degrees in Scotland constitute a distinct course of study, rather than a grade below honours degrees, they can be graded (from lowest to highest) as "pass", "merit" or "distinction".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] As in the rest of the UK, Certificates and Diplomas of Higher Education may be earned by those completing one and two years of a bachelor's degree course respectively.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The first two years, sometimes three, of both an ordinary degree and an honours degree are identical, but candidates for the ordinary degree study in less depth in their final year and often over a wider variety of subjects, and do not usually complete a dissertation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A Scottish ordinary degree is thus different from ordinary degrees in the rest of the UK in comprising a distinct course of study from the honours degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In keeping with the Scottish "broad education" philosophy, ordinary degrees (and more rarely honours ones) may mix different disciplines such as sciences and humanities taught in different faculties and in some cases even different universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees with honours are at level 10 of the Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework (SCQF) and require 480 credits with a minimum of 90 at level 10 and 90 at level 9.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Ordinary degrees are at level 9 and require 360 credits with a minimum of 90 at level 9.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Both honours degrees and ordinary degrees qualify as first cycle (end of cycle) qualifications in the Bologna Process.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science are at level 11 of the SCQF and are second cycle (end of cycle) qualifications in the Bologna Process.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In Australia, a "bachelor degree" is normally a three to four-year program, leading to a qualification at level 7 of the Australian Qualifications Framework.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Entry to a number of professions, such as law practice and teaching, require a bachelor's degree (a 'professional' degree).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Other degrees, such as Bachelor of Arts do not necessarily elicit entry into a profession, though many organisations require a bachelor's degree for employment.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A one-year postgraduate bachelor honours degree can be achieved as a consecutive stand-alone course following a bachelor's degree in the same field, or as an additional year as part of a bachelor's degree program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The honours course is normally only open to those who do well in their bachelor's degree program and involves study at a more advanced level than that bachelor's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Both the bachelor and bachelor honours degrees are aligned with level 6 of the EQF, the same as British and Irish bachelor's degrees with and without honours, and other Bologna Process first cycle qualifications.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some bachelor's degrees (e.g. engineering and environmental science) include an integrated honours degree as part of a four-year program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Honours is generally for students who want to take up a research track for postgraduate studies, and increasingly for those who want an extra edge in the job market.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor honours degrees include a major Independent research component, allowing students to develop skills that will enable them to proceed to further study or to work in research roles in industry.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] First-class or second-class (upper division) honours are generally required for entry into doctoral programs (e.g.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] PhDs, etc.); an alternative route to doctoral study is via a "masters degree".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The colonial link and the establishment of the University of the South Pacific in 1968 allowed the education system to follow suit from the qualification system of the Commonwealth.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] University of the South Pacific is the only university in the Oceania region to be internationally recognized outside Australia and New Zealand with its bachelor's and other awards program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is also the highest ranked in the university ranking in the island region and also ranked above some Australian universities like the University of Canberra, University of Sunshine Coast and New Zealand universities like Lincoln University and Waikato Institute of Technology.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In New Zealand, only recognised institutions – usually universities and polytechnics – have degree-awarding powers.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Most bachelor's degrees are three years full-time, but certain degrees, such as the Bachelor of Laws and the Bachelor of Engineering degrees, require four years of study.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A bachelor with honours is a program of four years duration (e.g., Bachelor of Arts with Honours).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A Bachelor of Medicine degree requires a minimum of six years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Where students opt to study two bachelor's degrees simultaneously – referred to as a "conjoint degree" or "double degree" – an extra year of study is added.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The number of years of study required is determined based on the degree with the greatest number of years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] For example, a BCom degree requires three years of full-time study, but a double BCom–LLB degree will require five years of full-time study because the LLB degree is four years long.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Exceptional students may choose to complete a degree in a shorter amount of time by taking on extra courses, usually with the help of summer school.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Students who complete a double degree program will have two separate bachelor's degrees at the end of their studies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Consistently high-performing students may also be invited to complete the 'honours' program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The bachelor with honours usually requires an extra year of study with an extra honours thesis/dissertation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] This degree is considered to fall between the bachelor's and master's levels on the European Qualifications Framework.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] An honours award is indicated by the addition of "Hons" to the degree name or abbreviation (for example, "Bachelor of Laws (Hons)").
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some honours degree courses also offer a postgraduate diploma (PGDip) as an exit qualification, which often consists of the same workload but with added flexibility.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A PGDip does not usually require a dissertation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] However, the student may complete one if desired.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A diploma award is indicated by "PGDip" and the degree field (for example, "PGDipArts" or "PGDipScience".
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Many other specialized bachelor's degrees are offered as well.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some are in very specialized areas, like the five-year BIDes or BScIDes degree in industrial design.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Others are offered only at a limited number of universities, such as the Walsh School of Foreign Service at Georgetown University's Bachelor of Science in Foreign Service (BSFS).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The University of Delaware offers a Bachelor of Applied Arts and Science (BAASc) degree, a degree which often indicates an interdisciplinary course of study for many majors within its School of Arts and Science.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Stanford University's Bachelor of Arts and Science degree is for students who are receiving one degree but who have completed two arts and sciences majors, one of which would ordinarily lead to the BA and one of which would ordinarily lead to the BSc.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Rules on this vary considerably, however.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Agriculture (BAgr) offers a broad training in the sciences.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The focus of this four-year applied degree is on the development of analytical, quantitative, computing and communication skills.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Students learn how to apply the knowledge and principles of science to the understanding and management of the production, processing and marketing of agricultural products, and to the management and conservation of our natural resources.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] This can include ecological agriculture.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Architecture (BArch) degree is a professional degree awarded to students who complete the five-year course of study in the field at some universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Many universities offer a BSc or BA (majoring in architecture) after the first three or four years, and then a post-graduate diploma, BArch or MArch for the following two to four years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Design (BDes) is awarded to those who complete the four- or four-and-a-half-year course of study in design, usually majoring in a specific field of design, such as interior design or graphic design.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Industrial Design (BID) is an undergraduate academic degree awarded by a university for a four-year course of study that specializes on the design of industrial products.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some colleges also offer four-year B.I.D. programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Arts degrees (BA, AB; also known as *Artium Baccalaureus*) along with the Bachelor of Science degrees are the most common undergraduate degrees given.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Originally, in the universities of Oxford, Cambridge and Dublin, all undergraduate degrees were in the faculty of arts, hence the name of the degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Applied Arts and Sciences (BAASc) is an undergraduate degree that bridges academic and work-life experiences.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] There are various undergraduate degrees in information technology incorporating programming, database design, software engineering, networks and information systems.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] These programs prepare graduates for further postgraduate research degrees or for employment in a variety of roles in the information technology industry.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The program focus may be on the technical or theoretical aspects of the subject matter, depending on which course is taken.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] A Bachelor of Economics (BEcon, BSc(Econ) and BEc) is awarded in British and Commonwealth institutions after following a rigorous programme of theoretical quantitative economic learning.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Programmes usually include study of both microeconomics and macroeconomics, alongside empirical work in the form of econometrics.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Economics can also be offered as a Bachelor of Science (with a more general focus on the quantitative methods) or a Bachelor of Arts (with a qualitative focus on the concepts).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Economics is substantially more theoretical and mathematical than the more commonly offered brethren.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In countries following British tradition (the University of Malta is an exception), medical students pursue an undergraduate medical education and receive bachelor's degrees in medicine and surgery (MBBChir, MBBS, BMBS, BM, MBChB, etc.).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Although notionally MB and BS are two degrees, they must be taken together.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In some Irish universities, a third degree, Bachelor of Arts in Obstetrics (BAO), is added.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] However, this third degree is an anachronism from the 19th century and is not registerable with the Irish Medical Council.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the UK, these qualifications, while retaining the title of bachelor's degrees, are master's degree level qualifications.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Use of the courtesy title of *doctor* is attached to the profession of doctor or physician and is granted by registration, not by earning the qualifying degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Trainee doctors in the UK are allowed to use the title once they begin their training and receive provisional registration.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Canadian MD degree is, despite its name, classified as a bachelor's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Dentistry is offered both as an undergraduate and a postgraduate course.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In countries following the British model, the first degree in dentistry is the Bachelor of Dental Surgery, which is a master's degree level qualification in the UK.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In some parts of the world, the doctorate of dental surgery (DDS) is the usual undergraduate program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Postgraduate courses such as the Bachelor of Dentistry (BDent) – awarded exclusively by the University of Sydney in Australia – require a previous bachelor's degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Midwifery degree is a professional degree awarded to students who have complete a three- to five-year (depending on the country) course of study in midwifery.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Common abbreviations include BScMid, BM, BMid and BHScMid.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Physiotherapy is offered both as an undergraduate and a graduate course of study.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Studies leading to the Bachelor of Physiotherapy (BPT) degree usually constitute the undergraduate program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the graduate program, courses leading to a degree such as the Master of Physiotherapy degree are offered.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the Canadian province of Quebec, French universities offer both undergraduate and graduate courses leading to the procurement of a Bachelor of Science degree with a major in physiotherapy and a Master of Science degree specialized in physiotherapy.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] McGill University, the Université de Montréal, and the Université de Sherbrooke are among the post-secondary institutions that offer such programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Optometry is a four-year or five-year course.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Although students graduate with a BSc after three years of study, passing a further supervised preregistration year is required to become a fully qualified optometrist.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The National Institute of Ophthalmic Sciences is among the post-secondary institutions that offer such programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It is the academic arm of The Tun Hussein Onn National Eye Hospital and the only eye hospital based institution in Malaysia.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Nursing degree is a three- to five-year undergraduate degree that prepares students for a career in nursing.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Often the degree is required to gain "registered nurse", or equivalent, status—subject to completion of exams in the area of residence.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Sometimes, though, the degree is offered only to nurses who are already registered.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Alternative titles include Bachelor of Science in Nursing and Bachelor of Nursing Science, with abbreviations BScN, BN and BNSc.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Paramedicine is offered both as an undergraduate and a postgraduate course in some countries.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Paramedicine (BScP, BP, BHScP) is a three- to a five-year undergraduate degree that prepares students for a career in paramedicine, paramedic services or emergency medical services.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Countries such as Canada, United Kingdom, Ireland, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa have established paramedicine degree programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The United States does not require a degree for paramedicine practice.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Veterinary Science program is generally a five-year course of study that is required for becoming a veterinarian.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It is also known as the Bachelor of Veterinary Medicine and Surgery at some universities (BVMS).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the UK, this is a master's degree level qualification that retains the title of bachelor's for historical reasons.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, no bachelor's degree of veterinary science is given, only the Doctor of Veterinary Medicine (DVM) degree is.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Pharmacy (BPharm) degree is a common undergraduate degree for the practice of pharmacy.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, Canada, and France, however, all colleges of pharmacy have now phased out the degree in favor of the PharmD, or doctor of pharmacy, degree or the PhD, doctor of philosophy, degree in pharmacy.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some universities, such as the University of Mississippi, award a Bachelor of Science in Pharmaceutical Sciences (BScPSc) degree as a part of the seven-year PharmD program after the completion of the first four years.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] However, the BScPSc degree does not qualify the recipient for the practice of pharmacy, for which students must earn a PharmD degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Public health is usually studied at the master's degree level.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Australia is one of the few countries where studies in Public Health are available at undergraduate level.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Indeed, Australian undergraduate students may major in specific areas of Public Health such as Health Promotion/Education, Epidemiology, Healthcare Administration and Public Health Nutrition.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science in Public Health (BScPH) degree is a four-year undergraduate degree that prepares students for careers in the public, private, or nonprofit sectors in areas such as public health, environmental health, health administration, epidemiology, or health policy and planning.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Kinesiology degree (BK or BScK)is a specialized degree in the field of human movement and kinetics.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some schools still offer the subject under the aegis of a School of Physical Education as a Bachelor of Physical Education (BPE or BPhEd), although "kinesiology" or "human kinetics" is currently the more popularly accepted term for the discipline.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The degree is awarded following four to six years of collegiate study in America (average five years), from three to four in Europe and Australia.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In America (especially Latin America), Nutrition per se is separated from Dietetics, where the latter is equivalent to a technical degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Aviation (BAv) is awarded to students who complete a four-year course of study in the field of aviation.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Traditionally, the BD was a graduate degree rather than a first degree and typically emphasised academic theology, biblical languages, etc.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] However, this has become a less common arrangement.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] While the theological bachelor's degree is generally conferred upon completion of a four-year program, it is also conferred in some specialized three-year programs.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] From there, the next level of advancement is generally the Master of Divinity (MDiv), Master of Theology (ThM), Master of Religious Studies, or Master of Religious Education (MRE) degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, the "mainline" Protestant clergy typically take a four-year bachelor's degree in whatever field they choose, then earn the MDiv (Master of Divinity) degree in an additional three years as part of preparation for ordination.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Fine Arts (BFA) degree is a specialized degree awarded for courses of study in the fine arts, frequently by an arts school or conservatory, although it is equally available at a significant number of traditional colleges and universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, the Bachelor of Fine Arts degree differs from a Bachelor of Arts degree in that the majority of the program consists of a practical studio component, as contrasted with lecture and discussion classes.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] A typical BFA program in the United States consists of two-thirds study in the arts, with one-third in more general liberal arts studies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] For a BA in art, the ratio might be reversed.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Film and Television (BFTV) degree is an undergraduate degree for the study of film and television production including areas of cinematography, directing, film production, script writing, sound, screenwriting, animation, and typography.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Integrated Studies (BIS) is an interdisciplinary bachelor's degree offered by several universities in the United States and Canada.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It allows students to design a customized and specific course of study to best suit their educational and professional objectives.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Generally, this degree is sponsored by two or more departments within the university.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Journalism (BAJ or BScJ) degree is a professional degree awarded to students who have studied journalism at a four-year accredited university.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Not all universities, however, grant this degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, schools tend to offer the BA or BS with a major in journalism instead.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The world's oldest school of journalism at the University of Missouri offers a BJ degree, not to be confused with the bachelor's degree in jurisprudence at Oxford University.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In South Africa, Rhodes University has the oldest school of journalism in Africa and allows students to take a fourth-year specialisation to raise their BA to BAJ status, equivalent to a BA (Hons).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Landscape Architecture (BLA) degree is awarded to students who complete the five- (in some countries four-) year course of study in the field.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Professional Studies is awarded to students who major in professional career studies.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Library Science or Bachelor of Library and Information Science (BLSc, BLISc) degree is sometimes awarded to students who major in library science, although Master of Library Science degrees are more common.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Music (BMus) degree is a professional or academic undergraduate degree in music at most conservatories in the US and the UK.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It is also commonly awarded at schools of music in large private or public universities.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Areas of study typically include music performance, music education, music therapy, music composition, academic fields (music history/musicology, music theory, ethnomusicology), and may include jazz, commercial music, recording technology, sacred music/music ministry, or music business.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Small liberal arts colleges and universities without schools of music often award only BA in music, with different sets of requirements.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] A Bachelor of Nonprofit and Nongovernmental Organization Studies is a field that focuses on practices of the nonprofit sector.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] A variety of higher education institutions and research organizations are dedicated to the teaching and research of issues related to the nonprofit sector.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Additionally, individual courses within related disciplines (e.g.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Business, Sociology, Public Policy) examine nonprofit studies in a variety of contexts.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Nonprofit studies may also refer to studies of the voluntary sector, third sector, nongovernmental organizations, or civil society.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Mortuary Science (BMS) is a professional undergraduate degree, awarded by the Cincinnati College of Mortuary Science of Cincinnati, Ohio and Southern Illinois University Carbondale.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It was introduced in 1986 and it is awarded to students that complete 120 semester hours of course work and receive passing scores on the National Board Exam administered by The International Conference of Funeral Service Examining Boards.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Philosophy (BPhil. or PhB) degree is either an undergraduate or graduate degree (MPhil).
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Generally, it entails independent research or a thesis/capstone project.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Variants include the Bachelor of Arts in Applied Psychology, Bachelor of Arts in Clinical Psychology, Bachelor of Arts in Forensic Psychology, Bachelor of Arts in Organizational Psychology.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Courses typically last four years, but may be as long as six.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Education degree (BEd) is a four-year undergraduate professional degree offered by many American colleges and universities for those preparing to be licensed as teachers.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Variants include the BEd, BAEd, BAT (Bachelor of Arts for Teaching), and BST degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Preparation for the MS in education, this degree is most often received by those interested in early childhood, elementary level, and special education, or by those planning to be school administrators.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Secondary level teachers often major in their subject area instead (i.e., history, chemistry, or mathematics), with a minor in education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some states require elementary teachers to choose a subject major as well, and minor in education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some universities also offer concurrent, five-year programs with student completing both a bachelor's degree in arts or science as well as their BEd.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The possession of a BEd and a second bachelor's degree is required to teach in most public anglophone and francophone schools in Canada.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The BEd prepares teachers for completion of either MA (Master of Arts) programs in education, MEd (Master of Education) programs, or postgraduate certificates in education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science and/with Education degree (BScEd) is a degree awarded to students who complete the four- to five-year course of study in the field of science (major and minor in general biology, chemistry, physics, and mathematics) and education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Although notionally BSc and BEd are two degrees, they must be taken together.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The graduates will work as science (physics, chemistry, biology) teachers in high schools, as lecturers in pre university colleges and matriculation centers and can progress to postgraduate programs (MSc and PhD) in various areas in science or education.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science in forestry (BScF) is a degree awarded to students who complete a three-year course of study in the field of forestry.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science degrees (BSc, ScB) along with the Bachelor of Arts degrees are the most common undergraduate degrees given.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science in Law degree (BScL) is a special-purpose degree that allows someone who has had some prior studies but has not achieved a bachelor's degree to resume his or her education and take up the study of law with the goal of eventually receiving the juris doctor degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Social Work (BSW) degree is a four-year undergraduate degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Usually the first two years consist of liberal arts courses and the last two years focus on social work classes in human development, policy/law, research, and practice.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Programs accredited by the Council on Social Work Education require BSW students to complete a minimum of 400 field education or internship hours.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Accredited BSW programs often allow students who are interested in obtaining a Master of Social Work degree to complete the degree in a shorter amount of time or waive courses.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In Latin America, this is a four to five-year degree that can replace liberal arts subjects into health sciences, resulting in social work as a type of community psychology and socioeconomic studies, focused in hospitals, prisons, or pedagogy, among others.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Technology degree (BTech) is a three- or four-year undergraduate degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Generally, the program is comparable to a Bachelor of Science degree program, which is additionally supplemented by either occupational placements (supervised practical or internships) or practice-based classroom courses.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Laws (LLB) is the principal academic degree in law in most common law countries other than the United States, and anglophone Canada, where it has been superseded by the juris doctor (JD) degree.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Talmudic Law degree (BTL) or a First Talmudic Degree (FTD) is the degree awarded in most Yeshivas around the United States.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The course would have an interdisciplinary approach with a vast range of units so the tourismologist professional would be able to identify necessary actions toward a sustainable touristic environment focus on local community uniqueness, values and traditions.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] As tourism is a growing industry, in India there is a lot of opportunity for those who complete this course of study.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It is available in select universities of India.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Mathematics or Bachelor of Mathematical Sciences degree (BMath and BMathSc) is given at the conclusion of a four-year honours program or a three-year general program.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Several universities, mostly in Canada and Australia, award such degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The usual degree for mathematics in all other countries is the BSc.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Urban and Regional Planning or Bachelor of Urban Planning or just Bachelor of Planning degree (BURP, BUP, or BPlan) is a degree offered at some institutions as a four or five-year professional undergraduate degree in urban planning.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Programs vary in their focus on studio work and may or may not involve professional practice.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Innovation is a four-year degree in a range of different fields.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The major fields, in engineering, business, arts, science or education, are similar to their associated BA or BSc degrees.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The general education elements are restructured to provide a common core of innovation, entrepreneurship and team skills.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The degree was created as a direct response to the increasing pace of innovation in today's society and the need for graduates that understanding effective teaming, as well as the innovation process.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] Nakanishi was born in Yokohama, Japan on March 14, 1946.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He studied electrical engineering at the University of Tokyo, obtaining a bachelor's degree in 1970 and joining Hitachi one month later.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He later attended Stanford University, receiving a master's degree in computer engineering in 1979.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] Nakanishi joined Hitachi's Omika Works Computer Control Design Department in 1970 immediately after graduating from college.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] His first management position was in the Information and Telecommunications Group.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He became the managing director of Hitachi Europe in 1998, before being promoted to senior vice president six years later.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He became the chairman of Hitachi America and chairman of Hitachi Global Storage Technologies in 2007.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] This was regarded as a "consolation prize" for being passed on as the parent company's president.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] However, he and other colleagues were called back to the parent group after it sustained record losses for a Japanese manufacturer in 2009.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] Nakanishi became president of Hitachi in 2010.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He started the Smart Transformation Project which restructured the company following the 2008 financial crisis, including the sale of HGST (Hitachi storage business) to Western Digital.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He established a board of directors at Hitachi similar to ones in the Western world, with non-executive directors holding a majority.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] Under his leadership, the company gradually decreased the number of its subsidiaries listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange from over twenty to just two.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] Nakanishi was chosen as chairman of the Japan Business Federation (Keidanren) in 2018.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] This was welcomed by local and international investors, who saw the election of the reformist Nakanishi to the conservative business lobby as recognition by the Keidanren that it needed to make improvements to corporate governance.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] As chairman, he advocated for the government to invest in digital technology, a drive supported by Yoshihide Suga upon becoming prime minister in 2020.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He was also instrumental in prompting the Federation to support the country's promise to become carbon neutral by 2050, in spite of its traditional opposition to climate change initiatives.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] Nakanishi received treatment for lymphoma starting in 2019.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He was hospitalized again in mid-July 2020, and reportedly in remission in March 2021.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] However, the cancer returned one month later, and he resigned as chairman of the Japan Business Federation at the end of May.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] This was the first time that the head of the business lobby resigned before completing his term.
[src:hiroaki-nakanishi/hiroaki-nakanishi] He died less than a month later on June 27, at the age of 75.
